cell("markdown","# Algorithms 29: K-Nearest Neighbors\n\n**Learning Objectives:**\n1. Differentiate Regression from Classification\n2. Implement the K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) classification algorithm\n3. Use Euclidean Distance to measure point similarity\n4. Use Leave-One-Out Cross Validation to choose the optimal hyperparameter $K$\n\n**Prerequisites:** Algorithms 26\n**Estimated time:** 60 minutes\n**Textbook:** *Justin Skycak — Intro to Algorithms & Machine Learning* Chapter 29"),
COLAB,
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase −1 — Theoretical Foundation\n\n### The K-Nearest Neighbors Algorithm\n> 📖 *From Algorithms Ch. 29:* Given a data set of points labeled with classes, KNN predicts the class of a new point by finding the $K$ points in the dataset nearest to the new point, and predicting the majority class of those neighbors.\n\nImagine we have a dataset of cookies: `(portion_butter, portion_sugar, type)`.\nType 0 is Shortbread, Type 1 is Sugar Cookie.\n\nIf we have a new cookie with `(0.25, 0.30)`, we compute the Euclidean distance $\\sqrt{(x_2-x_1)^2 + (y_2-y_1)^2}$ to every cookie in our dataset. If $K=3$, we look at the 3 closest cookies. If 2 are Shortbread and 1 is Sugar, we predict Shortbread!\n\n### Choosing K\nWe use **Leave-One-Out Cross Validation** (from Chapter 26). For every point in the dataset, we pretend we don't know its label, and try to predict it using the *rest* of the dataset. We sum up the accuracy for each $K$, and pick the $K$ with the highest accuracy!"),
cell("markdown","### Comprehension Check ✅\nWhy is it mathematically dangerous to use KNN on a dataset where `Butter` is measured in tiny decimals like $0.05$ cups, but `Sugar` is measured in huge integers like $300$ grams?\n\n<details><summary>💡 Answer</summary>\nBecause the Euclidean distance formula treats all axes equally! A difference of $10$ grams of sugar will absolutely overwhelm a difference of $0.1$ cups of butter in the distance formula. The algorithm will essentially ignore the butter. We must **Normalize** all variables to a $0-1$ scale before running KNN.\n</details>"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 0 — Math Foundation Practice\n\n### 🎯 Your Turn: Euclidean Distance\nWrite a function `distance(p1, p2)` that computes the Euclidean distance between two points (which can have any number of dimensions)."),
