cell("code","def predict_knn(training_data, new_point, k):\n    distances = []\n    # 1. Loop through training_data. Compute distance to new_point.\n    # Append (dist, label) to distances list.\n    # YOUR CODE HERE\n    \n    # 2. Sort the distances list by the first element (the distance)\n    # YOUR CODE HERE\n    \n    # 3. Slice the top k elements. Extract their labels.\n    # YOUR CODE HERE\n    \n    # 4. Return the most common label. (In case of a tie, you can just pick the first one, or write logic to sum total distances of the tied classes!)\n    # YOUR CODE HERE\n    pass"),
cell("markdown","### Step 2: Leave-One-Out Cross Validation\nWrite a function `evaluate_knn(data, k)` that performs cross-validation and returns the accuracy (from 0.0 to 1.0)."),
cell("code","def evaluate_knn(data, k):\n    correct = 0\n    # For each point in data:\n    #   Remove it to form training_data\n    #   Call predict_knn on it\n    #   If prediction == actual label, correct += 1\n    \n    # YOUR CODE HERE\n    \n    return correct / len(data)"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 2 — Experimental Verification\n\n### Finding the Best K\nHere is a synthetic dataset of cookies. Let's plot the accuracy for $K = 1, 2, \\dots, 9$."),
