cell("markdown","# Algorithms 30: Naive Bayes Classification\n\n**Learning Objectives:**\n1. Formulate classification using Bayes' Theorem\n2. Understand the \"Naive\" independence assumption\n3. Implement a probabilisitic classifier that calculates $P(Class | Data)$\n\n**Prerequisites:** Algorithms 29\n**Estimated time:** 60 minutes\n**Textbook:** *Justin Skycak — Intro to Algorithms & Machine Learning* Chapter 30"),
COLAB,
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase −1 — Theoretical Foundation\n\n### Bayesian Probability\n> 📖 *From Algorithms Ch. 30:* Naive Bayes is grounded in Bayesian probability. It chooses the class with the highest conditional probability given the data point, assuming that all the variables in the dataset are independent from each other.\n\nFrom Bayes' Theorem: \n$$P(\\text{class} \\mid \\text{point}) = \\frac{P(\\text{point} \\mid \\text{class}) P(\\text{class})}{P(\\text{point})}$$\n\nSince $P(\\text{point})$ is the same for all classes, we just want to maximize the numerator: $P(\\text{point} \\mid \\text{class}) P(\\text{class})$.\n\n### The \"Naive\" Assumption\nA point has multiple features $(x_1, x_2, \\dots)$. Calculating the exact joint probability $P(x_1, x_2 \\mid \\text{class})$ is nearly impossible. \nBut if we Naively assume the features are strictly independent, we can multiply them!\n$$P(x_1, x_2 \\mid \\text{class}) \\approx P(x_1 \\mid \\text{class}) \\times P(x_2 \\mid \\text{class})$$\n\nThus, the formula becomes:\n$\\text{Score} = P(\\text{class}) \\times P(x_1 \\mid \\text{class}) \\times P(x_2 \\mid \\text{class})$\n\nThe algorithm computes this score for every possible class, and predicts the class with the highest score!"),
cell("markdown","### Comprehension Check ✅\nWhy is the independence assumption called \"Naive\"?\n\n<details><summary>💡 Answer</summary>\nBecause features in the real world are almost never perfectly independent! For example, if predicting whether an animal is a Dog, the feature \"Has Fur\" and \"Barks\" are heavily correlated. Treating them as independent statistical events is a mathematical fiction, but it turns out to work remarkably well in practice anyway.\n</details>"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 0 — Math Foundation Practice\n\n### 🎯 Your Turn: Continuous Probability Density\nIf our features are continuous numbers (like height or weight), we use the Gaussian (Normal) Distribution PDF to estimate $P(x \\mid \\text{class})$:\n$$P(x \\mid \\mu, \\sigma) = \\frac{1}{\\sigma \\sqrt{2\\pi}} e^{-\\frac{1}{2} (\\frac{x - \\mu}{\\sigma})^2}$$\nWrite a function `gaussian_pdf(x, mean, stdev)`."),
cell("code","import math\ndef gaussian_pdf(x, mean, stdev):\n    # Prevent division by zero if stdev is exactly 0\n    if stdev == 0: stdev = 1e-6\n    # YOUR CODE HERE\n    pass\n\n# assert abs(gaussian_pdf(0, 0, 1) - 0.3989) < 1e-3"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 1 — Algorithm Construction\n\n### Step 1: Calculate Statistics\nWrite a function `summarize_by_class(dataset)` that groups the data by class, and for each class, computes the `(mean, stdev)` for each feature.\n`dataset` is `[(features_tuple, label)]`."),
cell("code","def mean(numbers):\n    return sum(numbers) / float(len(numbers))\n\ndef stdev(numbers):\n    avg = mean(numbers)\n    variance = sum((x - avg)**2 for x in numbers) / float(len(numbers) - 1 + 1e-6)\n    return math.sqrt(variance)\n\ndef summarize_by_class(dataset):\n    separated = {}\n    # 1. Group rows by class\n    for features, label in dataset:\n        if label not in separated:\n            separated[label] = []\n        separated[label].append(features)\n        \n    # 2. Compute (mean, stdev) for each feature in each class\n    summaries = {}\n    for label, rows in separated.items():\n        # ZIP trick to group columns: list(zip(*rows))\n        # YOUR CODE HERE\n        pass\n        \n    return summaries"),
cell("markdown","### Step 2: Prediction\nWrite `predict_naive_bayes(summaries, point)`.\nFor each class, compute $P(\\text{class}) \\times \\prod P(x_i \\mid \\text{mean}_i, \\text{stdev}_i)$.\nReturn the class with the highest probability score."),
cell("code","def predict_naive_bayes(summaries, total_rows, class_counts, point):\n    best_label, best_prob = None, -1\n    \n    # for label, class_summaries in summaries.items():\n    #     prob = class_counts[label] / total_rows # P(class)\n    #     for i in range(len(class_summaries)):\n    #         mean, stdev = class_summaries[i]\n    #         prob *= gaussian_pdf(point[i], mean, stdev) # P(xi | class)\n    #     \n    #     if best_label is None or prob > best_prob:\n    #         best_prob = prob\n    #         best_label = label\n            \n    # return best_label\n    pass"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 2 — Experimental Verification\n\n### The Gender Dataset\nLet's predict gender based on `(Height(ft), Weight(lbs), Foot Size(in))`."),
cell("code","data = [\n    ((6.00, 180, 12), \"M\"), ((5.92, 190, 11), \"M\"), ((5.58, 170, 12), \"M\"), ((5.92, 165, 10), \"M\"),\n    ((5.00, 100, 6), \"F\"), ((5.50, 150, 8), \"F\"), ((5.42, 130, 7), \"F\"), ((5.75, 150, 9), \"F\")\n]\n\n# summaries = summarize_by_class(data)\n# class_counts = {\"M\": 4, \"F\": 4}\n\n# new_person = (6.0, 130, 8)\n# prediction = predict_naive_bayes(summaries, 8, class_counts, new_person)\n# print(\"Prediction for (6.0, 130, 8):\", prediction) # Should probably be Female due to weight and foot size!"),
